1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
 Hello. Welcome to Django for Everybody. My name is Charles Severance and I've developed these materials that I hope you find useful.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:16,000
 So one of the things I like to do whenever I start teaching a class is explain why I chose to teach this material.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:23,000
 In particular, why Django? To explain why Django, I have to go back into the past a little bit.

4
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:34,000
 I have been teaching here at the School of Information, University of Michigan, since 2007, I've been teaching web development.

5
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:45,000
 And if we go all the way back to the beginning, I think we started with PHP, then we did Ruby on Rails, and then we did Google App Engine.

6
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:53,000
 I even wrote a textbook for O'Reilly and Associates about Google App Engine. We used that textbook for a while.

7
00:00:53,000 --> 00:01:02,000
 It was based on Django 1.0 and then they changed Google App Engine and I didn't like that because it broke my book.

8
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:17,000
 And then we switched to PHP and then we did Flask and then we did Django. So there's a whole litany of different web development frameworks we've used over the years.

9
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:22,000
 And that's kind of how web development is. There's always something new, always something different.

10
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:33,000
 So right before I was teaching Django for everybody, I was teaching PHP and I had been teaching that for five years and I just love that class.

11
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:39,000
 We teach Python for most of our beginning students and just that's a great first language.

12
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:49,000
 That course that I built that taught Python to beginners evolved into the course Python for Everybody, which is one of the most popular programming courses in the world.

13
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:57,000
 And one of the things that I wanted to do was teach a second language, not just more Python, so that's why I really like teaching PHP.

14
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:09,000
 And I developed that course for five years, but it wasn't just a PHP class. It was HTML, it's CSS, JavaScript, jQuery, JSON, PHP.

15
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:18,000
 And I love teaching that class, but at some point the curriculum committee wanted it to be Python across the board.

16
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:25,000
 I love that course and I turned it into web applications for everybody and that's available also online.

17
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 And so I had a year to convert from PHP to Python. And so during that year I asked myself the question, would I teach Flask or Django?

18
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:42,000
 And I had a semester sabbatical and during that time someone taught the class in Flask.

19
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:50,000
 And I looked at what they were accomplishing in the 15th week of the Flask class and I'm like, oh, there's so much low level stuff you have to learn.

20
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:57,000
 And so I was like, I'm not sure I like Flask, but I had a year. So I asked everyone I knew who was pretty sharp.

21
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 I said, would you prefer Flask or Django? And the strange thing is I got different answers.

22
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 Half the people said Flask is great, Django is terrible, and the other half the people said Django is great, Flask is terrible, which was inconclusive.

23
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:19,000
 And then I changed the question. I said, if you were going to teach only one of Flask or Django, which one would you teach first?

24
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:24,000
 And at that point, Django was pretty much the consensus agreement.

25
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:32,000
 And that's because Flask is a very powerful tool in the hands of strong developers.

26
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:43,000
 So if you're teaching, taking a React class or a Progressive Web Applications class and you just want kind of a little back end and you know what you're doing,

27
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:47,000
 Flask is great because you whip up a little microservice and away it goes.

28
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:56,000
 But Django, if you don't know anything, Django gives you a road to follow. You go down this road and you will learn and you will build something.

29
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:04,000
 And so I started developing this class. It took me a couple of years to get it right. I iterate a lot.

30
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:10,000
 I'm an engineer and I love to iterate. After a couple of years, I said, OK, I think I like it.

31
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:15,000
 And so I turned it into this DJ for E, Django for everybody. It became a MOOC.

32
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:21,000
 And so I'm really impressed at how far we get.

33
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 And the reason is, is with Django, because there's kind of a road and you follow the road.

34
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 At the end, my students have a nicely working website that has Ajax working, has pictures working, has single sign-on using OAuth working and all these things.

35
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 And we learn about Bootstrap and a whole bunch of things.

36
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:48,000
 And if you look at their website, you know, it's a beginner, but it is a complete website.

37
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:54,000
 And because we use Python Anywhere, they are hosting it from the first week.

38
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 So every assignment is in a hosted Python Anywhere instance of Django for them.

39
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 And so they're learning how to host. And I think that's of all the things I've taught up to this point.

40
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 I never, other than Google App Engine, I never could get the students to have in effect a URL at the end of the course.

41
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:22,000
 This is a great second class, once you kind of know Python, to learn how to use Python to do something.

42
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 It's advanced Python. It's using things that you might have seen in initial Python class, but not really developed skill in.

43
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:36,000
 And the particular skill that this class really is going to teach you is object oriented programming.

44
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 And I'll just say, object oriented programming is probably one of the most important concepts in programming.

45
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:49,000
 And it's also the most difficult concept to teach and learn.

46
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 That's because if you just take a class and you have a chapter on object orientation, you'll see a bunch of syntax.

47
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,000
 But you do not know why you're using that syntax.

48
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:01,000
 Whereas in Django, on the first day you're building objects.

49
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:08,000
 Django itself is an object and you're like overriding bits and pieces inside of this big object.

50
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,000
 And then there's objects within objects.

51
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:17,000
 And so it's a wonderful, wonderful way to teach object oriented programming in Django.

52
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:22,000
 And so in this class, I review Python's object oriented programming.

53
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:30,000
 I feature all of the use of objects in Django when I say object many, many times, just like I'm saying in this little intro video.

54
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 But then we also later look at JavaScript.

55
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:37,000
 And then we look at object oriented programming in JavaScript as well.

56
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 And they're different.

57
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 The execution model for Python and the execution model for JavaScript object orientation is a little bit different.

58
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:55,000
 And so for me, that sort of compare and contrast is a really great opportunity as a teacher

59
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 to get students to understand the principles of object orientation and not be just looking at the various syntaxes.

60
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:08,000
 So with that, welcome to a course that I think is a great course and I hope that you enjoy it.

61
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 And I wish you luck.

62
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:11,000
 Take your time.

63
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 Don't rush.

64
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:16,000
 These kind of learning experiences are precious.

65
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,000
 And take your time and learn everything.

66
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 And I wish you nothing but the best.

67
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:22,000
 And I hope to see you online.

68
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 Cheers.

69
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:33,000
 [music]

